{{Infobox scientist | name = Merieme Chadid | image = Merieme Chadid.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1969|10|11}} | nationality = [[France]] and [[Morocco]] | fields = [[Astronomy]] and [[Exploration]] | workplaces = [[Dome Charlie]], Antarctica | alma_mater = Ph.D. [[Paul Sabatier University]] | known_for = Astronomer and Explorer | awards = Young Global Leader 2008 in the [[World Economic Forum]]. Woman of the Year 2015 in Science. Officer of [[Order of Ouissam Alaouite]] handed over by His Majesty The [[King of Morocco]] in 2013. Woman of the Antarctic Wikibomb by Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research SCAR in 2016. Young Leader of the France-China Foundation in 2014.
| website = }}
'''Merieme Chadid''' (born October 11, 1969 in [[Casablanca]]) is a [[Morocco|Moroccan]]-[[France|French]] [[astronomer]], [[explorer]] and [[research]]er at the [[University of Nice Sophia Antipolis]].<ref name="Miller-2018"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Featured Fellow: Dr. Merieme Chadid, Renowned Astronomer and Explorer |website=africaprosperity.com |publisher=The Global Network for Africa's Prosperity |url=http://africaprosperity.com/index.php/about-us/newsletter/96-merieme-chadid |access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> In 2005, she led an international scientific program to install a major astronomical observatory at [[Dome Charlie]] in the heart of Antarctica.<ref name="Miller-2018"/><ref name="AGN-2012"/><ref name="Bio"/>
== Career == Chadid received her Ph.D from the [[Paul Sabatier University]], Toulouse, in 1996, discovering and explaining hypersonic shock waves in pulsating stars. She then joined the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]] in Montpelier. From 1998 to 2001 she worked on installation of the [[Very Large Telescope]] in Chile and in 2002 joined the Conseil national des Astronomes.<ref name="AGN-2012"/>
In 2005 Chadid lead her first expedition to install telescopes for a new [[Dome C#Astronomical observatory|astronomical observatory]] in the heart of Antarctica. She was the first woman astronomer to set foot in Antarctica and the first to place the Moroccan flag at the South pole.<ref name="AGN-2012"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moroccanembassylondon.org.uk/en/InspiringMorocco.html|title=Arab Woman of The Year 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=moroccanembassylondon.org.uk|publisher=Embassy of The Kingdom of Morocco|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref>
